{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1288"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1288"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.1,0.03,0.06,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1288"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1288"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-11-30T14:05:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T15:40:12+09:30","updatedAction":"updated","acceptedAt":"2024-08-08T09:17:23+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-25 11:23:02"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1288"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92639"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41647"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92639"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with left upper quadrant pain after falling over and striking her upper abdomen against a chair. Her blood pressure is 120/80 and pulse 90/min. She has some bruising immediately under the rib cage, but no other abnormal physical findings. A CT of the abdomen and pelvis is normal, apart from a 5.5 cm unilocular right sided ovarian cyst. It is thin-walled and there are no septations. On review, the patient has no menstrual irregularities and uses the oral contraceptive pill.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With regards to the CT findings, which one of the following is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound follow-up","Serum Ca125","Percutaneous aspiration of the cyst","Laparoscopic cyst removal","Reassurance"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an incidental finding of a simple, likely functional, ovarian cyst that currently does not require any intervention. Simple cysts often resolve spontaneously. They are physiological follicular cysts that have no malignant potential, and are characterised by smooth thin walls, no septation, no solid component and posterior acoustic enhancement. It is important that the discharge summary includes the presence of the cyst and recommends a\u003Cstrong\u003E repeat pelvic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E in 2 - 4 months through the General Practitioner. Many of these cysts will resolve spontaneously. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor asymptomatic ovarian cysts under 5cm, no further follow up would be required so \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance \u003C/strong\u003Ealone would not be appropriate in this case due to the size of the cyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECa125\u003C/strong\u003E in a woman of this age with findings characteristic of a benign cyst would be unlikely to change management and has low sensitivity in a pre-menopausal woman. If there were additional concerns not featured in this case, a risk of malignancy index (RMI) could be done with an ultrasound and Ca125.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAttempted \u003Cstrong\u003Easpiration of the cyst\u003C/strong\u003E would be meddlesome and poses risk of damage to bowel or blood vessels unecessarily. Furthermore, if an abdominal cystic lesion is thought to have malignant potential, aspiration should be avoided because of the risk of spillage of malignant cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there was evidence of cyst rupture with active and ongoing haemorrhage or malignant features, then \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic removal of the cyst\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered, however there is no evidence in this scenario. The risks of the operation would outweigh any benefits in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-feta protein \u003C/strong\u003E(AFP) can be elevated in germ tumours however there were no malignant features in the history or ultrasound finding, and thus is unlikely to be of benefit in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most simple ovarian cysts in pre-menopausal women resolve spontaneously."],"references":["RCOG (2011). Green Top Guideline No. 62. Management of Suspected Ovarian Masses in Premenopausal Women. https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/gtg_62.pdf","Bottomley C, Bourne T. Diagnosis and management of ovarian cyst accidents. Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol. 2009;23(5):711-724. doi:10.1016/j.bpobgyn.2009; 23:711-24","Yeoh M, Investigation and management of an ovarian mass. Aust Fam Phys. 2015; 44:48-52. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25688960/","Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Management of suspected ovarian masses in premenopausal women (Green-top Guideline No. 62) [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2011 [cited 2024 Nov 23]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/ovarian-masses-in-preme","Bethune M. How to manage a complex ovarian cyst. O\u0026G\u202fMagazine. 2020\u202fAutumn;22(1). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/22/1-22/how-to-manage-a-complex-ovarian-cyst/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92639"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1288"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92639"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-30T15:39:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T15:39:58+09:30","number":7,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1288"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110366"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"